    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-05-21T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-05-21T11:00:00-05:00" n="425"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d425">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">832.00 Revolutions/605: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Brazil</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Caffery</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Rio de Janeiro</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-05-21T13:00:00-03:00"
                            >May 21, 1938—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 3:40 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>120. For the Under Secretary. Department’s 68. President Vargas, Aranha, Minister
                    of War, Chief of General Staff, Chief of President’s Military Household, all
                    strongly suspect that German representatives here had knowledge of and much
                    sympathy with uprising and possibly took part in plans therefor but thus far
                    they have no definite proof. Due [apparently garbled] Attaché of the German
                    Embassy, Aranha says, is returning to Germany by special plane.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Caffery</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
